				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$gO = 100\% \times \pi _3{\mathrm{/}}(\pi _1 + \pi _2 + \pi _3)$$\end{document}gO=100%×π3/(π1+π2+π3). DD based results showed strong convergence with smaller credible intervals (CIs) because of its large sample size as well as high relative risks of DNMs (Fig. 4a/b, Supplementary Table 1). As expected, high gOs were observed for pairs of DD, ID, and ASD (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
